 OK, so what are you talking about?

69
00:02:40,440 --> 00:02:43,760
 I'm talking about synesthesia.

70
00:02:43,760 --> 00:02:45,440
 So you may have heard of synesthesia.

71
00:02:45,440 --> 00:02:46,680
 I'm a synesthet.

72
00:02:46,680 --> 00:02:50,640
 So I was diagnosed with synesthesia when I was 19 at university.

73
00:02:50,640 --> 00:02:52,240
 And I've got several types.

74
00:02:52,240 --> 00:02:56,480
 But the main one is graphene color synesthesia.

75
00:02:56,480 --> 00:02:59,240
 So that means that numbers, letters, days of the week,

76
00:02:59,240 --> 00:03:01,840
 any abstract concepts have a color.

77
00:03:01,840 --> 00:03:03,840
 And I always say, it doesn't mean I see auras.

78
00:03:03,840 --> 00:03:06,080
 I know I'm for Christ, but not that person.

79
00:03:06,080 --> 00:03:08,680
 It's hard to explain when you are a synesthene.

80
00:03:08,680 --> 00:03:11,960
 Because the reason I didn't know I had it till I was 19

81
00:03:11,960 --> 00:03:14,680
 is because we all just sort of assume everyone's brain

82
00:03:14,680 --> 00:03:16,880
 works broadly the same as ours.

83
00:03:16,880 --> 00:03:18,160
 And so I don't know--

84
00:03:18,160 --> 00:03:19,920
 I don't understand how you don't have colors.

85
00:03:19,920 --> 00:03:21,040
 Can I ask a question?

86
00:03:21,040 --> 00:03:21,640
 You may.

87
00:03:21,640 --> 00:03:23,480
 You have a sheet of paper in front of you.

88
00:03:23,480 --> 00:03:23,720
 I do.

89
00:03:23,720 --> 00:03:24,960
 It's black and white.

90
00:03:24,960 --> 00:03:25,280
 Yes.

91
00:03:25,280 --> 00:03:28,480
 When you look at that, is it like the colored in the letters?

92
00:03:28,480 --> 00:03:29,080
 Or is it whatever?

93
00:03:29,080 --> 00:03:32,920
 So some people have a sort of synesthesia which is projected.

94
00:03:32,920 --> 00:03:34,560
 So they do exactly that.

95
00:03:34,560 --> 00:03:37,000
 It sort of changes color when they look at it.

96
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:38,320
 For me, it's very internal.

97
00:03:38,320 --> 00:03:41,600
 So it's in my mind's eye, if you like, one of the better words.

98
00:03:41,600 --> 00:03:41,800
 Yes.

99
00:03:41,800 --> 00:03:44,800
 So I'm currently part of a study at Sussex University.

100
00:03:44,800 --> 00:03:47,400
 There's Professor Julia Simner at Sussex Uni.

101
00:03:47,400 --> 00:03:50,400
 And she specializes in perception and synesthesia.

102
00:03:50,400 --> 00:03:52,560
 And I wrote to her a couple of years ago

103
00:03:52,560 --> 00:03:57,120
 because when I think every thought I have

104
00:03:57,120 --> 00:03:59,800
 is in a physical location from the real world.

105
00:03:59,800 --> 00:04:03,000
 So when I think about the number four, it's always in the sky.

106
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:03,760
 But it's orange.

107
00:04:03,760 --> 00:04:05,880
 So it's all floating orange in the sky.

108
00:04:05,880 --> 00:04:09,880
 And so I contacted her to say, is this a form of synesthesia?

109
00:04:09,880 --> 00:04:11,280
 And she said, well, I've never heard of it,

110
00:04:11,280 --> 00:04:12,600
 but let's do a study.

111
00:04:12,600 --> 00:04:14,520
 And so they found a handful of people

112
00:04:14,520 --> 00:04:16,960
 that seemed to experience the same thing.

113
00:04:16,960 --> 00:04:18,200
 And so she's studying it.

114
00:04:18,200 --> 00:04:21,320
 She's calling it conception, location, synesthesia,

115
00:04:21,320 --> 00:04:22,520
 is what she's calling it.

116
00:04:22,520 --> 00:04:25,400
 But also, if you heard of Adam Zeman,

117
00:04:25,400 --> 00:04:29,280
 so he's the man who came up with the word aphantasia

118
00:04:29,280 --> 00:04:31,520
 for people who have no internal images.

119
00:04:31,520 --> 00:04:32,360
 Like me.

120
00:04:32,360 --> 00:04:33,640
 Oh, do you have aphantasia?

121
00:04:33,640 --> 00:04:35,560
 So Julia's very interested in that as well.

122
00:04:35,560 --> 00:04:37,160
 What a sandwich, I'm sitting in.

123
00:04:37,160 --> 00:04:38,160
 Right.

124
00:04:38,160 --> 00:04:40,360
 In between synesthesia and aphantasia.

125
00:04:40,360 --> 00:04:42,320
 I thought all the images that you don't have in my brain, basically.

126
00:04:42,320 --> 00:04:43,800
 It feels a bit greedy, really, actually.

127
00:04:43,800 --> 00:04:44,800
 I'll be honest.

128
00:04:44,800 --> 00:04:46,320
 Well, there was a massive coincidence.

129
00:04:46,320 --> 00:04:49,120
 It was about two years ago I contacted Julia.

130
00:04:49,120 --> 00:04:52,560
 And around the same time, Adam Zeman contacted her

131
00:04:52,560 --> 00:04:54,720
 and said, I've had someone get in touch

132
00:04:54,720 --> 00:04:58,400
 to describe this phenomenon about location when they're thinking.

133
00:04:58,400 --> 00:04:59,560
 And she said, oh, that must be Angela.

134
00:04:59,560 --> 00:05:00,600
 She contacted me as well.

135
00:05:00,600 --> 00:05:02,760
 And he said, no, it's someone else entirely.

136
00:05:02,760 --> 00:05:05,360
 And it just happened to be within the same two weeks.

137
00:05:05,360 --> 00:05:07,520
 So they're now both doing studies on this.

138
00:05:07,520 --> 00:05:08,760
 On telekinesis.

139
00:05:08,760 --> 00:05:10,880
 On telekinesis, if only with that.

140
00:05:10,880 --> 00:05:12,120
 It's morphic resonance, I think.

141
00:05:12,120 --> 00:05:12,960
 Yeah, actually.

142
00:05:12,960 --> 00:05:13,800
 Thank you.

143
00:05:13,800 --> 00:05:17,400
 Calling it, it's quite, he's calling it topo phantasia, which makes sense.

144
00:05:17,400 --> 00:05:22,640
 So there is a thing of, I mean, I'm not synesthesiatical.

145
00:05:22,640 --> 00:05:24,440
 A synesthetic.

146
00:05:24,440 --> 00:05:27,280
 A synesthesiatical.

147
00:05:27,280 --> 00:05:28,520
 But I don't have any phantasia.

148
00:05:28,520 --> 00:05:30,840
 But I do have the, I'm sure lots of people

149
00:05:30,840 --> 00:05:32,640
 have the location specific.

150
00:05:32,640 --> 00:05:35,760
 A sensory thing triggers a spatial memory.

151
00:05:35,760 --> 00:05:39,440
 So if I smell green chilies roasting, I'm in New Mexico.

152
00:05:39,440 --> 00:05:40,920
 And it's autumn, you know?

153
00:05:40,920 --> 00:05:42,920
 So that's very linked to memory.

154
00:05:42,920 --> 00:05:45,760
 So that's really common that when we smell something,

155
00:05:45,760 --> 00:05:48,680
 the thing with synesthesia is there isn't a link.

156
00:05:48,680 --> 00:05:50,360
 You've just described memory.

157
00:05:50,360 --> 00:05:51,040
 No, no, no.

158
00:05:51,040 --> 00:05:53,040
 And she was politely saying, it's a really common thing.

159
00:05:53,040 --> 00:05:55,040
 So for me, it's if I smell baked beans cooking,

160
00:05:55,040 --> 00:05:56,480
 I'm in my full canteen.

161
00:05:56,480 --> 00:05:58,560
 That's kind of, you're really common, Andy.

162
00:05:58,560 --> 00:06:00,080
 But it's, don't lie, man.

163
00:06:00,080 --> 00:06:03,000
 What I'm trying to say is it triggers a specific,

164
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:05,600
 like a specific sensation triggers a really specific memory.

165
00:06:05,600 --> 00:06:06,760
 Prusky, yeah.

166
00:06:06,760 --> 00:06:09,360
 So what they think is with people with synesthesia

167
00:06:09,360 --> 00:06:11,600
 is what one of the, there's lots of theories

168
00:06:11,600 --> 00:06:13,840
 and they don't know exactly what causes synesthesia.

169
00:06:13,840 --> 00:06:16,120
 They do, they have worked out that it's hereditary

170
00:06:16,120 --> 00:06:19,240
 and then it's, to do with the X chromosome.

171
00:06:19,240 --> 00:06:22,280
 But what they think happens is that when you're a child

172
00:06:22,280 --> 00:06:24,720
 before you acquire language, you obviously

173
00:06:24,720 --> 00:06:27,040
 have to interpret the world around you in a different way

174
00:06:27,040 --> 00:06:28,000
 without words.

175
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:31,320
 And so you have this extra white matter,

176
00:06:31,320 --> 00:06:34,520
 extra connections in your brain to different parts

177
00:06:34,520 --> 00:06:35,480
 of your brain.

178
00:06:35,480 --> 00:06:38,040
 And in most people, they sort of get pruned away

179
00:06:38,040 --> 00:06:39,360
 as you don't need them anymore.

180
00:06:39,360 --> 00:06:40,040
 Right.

181
00:06:40,040 --> 00:06:41,880
 And then, but with people with synesthesia,

182
00:06:41,880 --> 00:06:44,240
 those connections don't get pruned, they stay.

183
00:06:44,240 --> 00:06:49,400
 And so what it means is that you get a sort of an odd reaction

184
00:06:49,400 --> 00:06:53,320
 to a stimulus, and by odds, I just mean one that isn't typical.

185
00:06:53,320 --> 00:06:56,960
 So for someone with synesthesia, a part of my brain

186
00:06:56,960 --> 00:06:59,480
 gets triggered when I see a certain letter

187
00:06:59,480 --> 00:07:01,520
 or I hear something or whatever

188
00:07:01,520 --> 00:07:04,400
 that wouldn't normally be triggered in that situation.

189
00:07:04,400 --> 00:07:06,760
 And so it's just a hyper-connected brain.

190
00:07:06,760 --> 00:07:07,800
 Look, they call it.

191
00:07:07,800 --> 00:07:09,080
 And so there's lots of things to go with it,

192
00:07:09,080 --> 00:07:11,720
 like, misophonia, misekinesia, all these things.

193
00:07:11,720 --> 00:07:12,840
 People with synesthesia tend to do that.

194
00:07:12,840 --> 00:07:14,720
 So you hate to when people are chewing next to you?

195
00:07:14,720 --> 00:07:15,960
 I hate to when people are chewing next to you.

196
00:07:15,960 --> 00:07:17,400
 I have really strong misophonia.

197
00:07:17,400 --> 00:07:19,160
 I am synesthesiatic.

198
00:07:19,160 --> 00:07:20,840
 [LAUGHTER]

199
00:07:20,840 --> 00:07:23,880
 You can have misophonia, and yeah, it's really--

200
00:07:23,880 --> 00:07:25,520
 What about people putting their feet on the seats

201
00:07:25,520 --> 00:07:26,360
 on the train?

202
00:07:26,360 --> 00:07:29,600
 Is that a special power that I have to find that annoying?

203
00:07:29,600 --> 00:07:33,560
 Well, I think you're just a bit old man.

204
00:07:33,560 --> 00:07:34,880
 I don't think it could be that bad.

205
00:07:34,880 --> 00:07:37,720
 I think everyone should be angry with people

206
00:07:37,720 --> 00:07:38,720
 in their fields.

207
00:07:38,720 --> 00:07:40,080
 I think that's everything.

208
00:07:40,080 --> 00:07:42,760
 But misekinesia is something that, again, I only recently--

209
00:07:42,760 --> 00:07:45,400
 I had a meeting with Julia a couple of months ago,

210
00:07:45,400 --> 00:07:47,560
 just to sort of see how the study was going and stuff.

211
00:07:47,560 --> 00:07:49,520
 So I'm hoping to write a book about it.

212
00:07:49,520 --> 00:07:53,640
 And she told me about misekinesia, which really made me go,

213
00:07:53,640 --> 00:07:54,800
 oh, yes, I have that.

214
00:07:54,800 --> 00:07:56,800
 My husband is what I'd call a jiggula,

215
00:07:56,800 --> 00:07:59,080
 one of those feet just doesn't stop moving, consciously.

216
00:07:59,080 --> 00:08:00,960
 If I can see a part of his body moving out

217
00:08:00,960 --> 00:08:03,720
 of the corner of my eye, it drives me insane.

218
00:08:03,720 --> 00:08:07,440
 If I can just see a movement, and they call it misekinesia,

219
00:08:07,440 --> 00:08:09,200
 as she told me, it made me feel better about it.

220
00:08:09,200 --> 00:08:11,240
 It might make you feel better about your misophonia,

221
00:08:11,240 --> 00:08:14,800
 is that apparently it's the salience network in your brain,

222
00:08:14,800 --> 00:08:17,640
 which is activated when you have misophonia.

223
00:08:17,640 --> 00:08:20,120
 And it is the same reaction, basically.

224
00:08:20,120 --> 00:08:22,960
 She describes it to me as if a bear had walked in the room.

225
00:08:22,960 --> 00:08:23,480
 Yeah.

226
00:08:23,480 --> 00:08:26,080
 So it's sort of that ancient part of your brain being triggered.

227
00:08:26,080 --> 00:08:26,680
 That's right.

228
00:08:26,680 --> 00:08:27,840
 I'm really interested, Angela.

229
00:08:27,840 --> 00:08:31,240
 OK, so that's the colors we talked about a little bit.

230
00:08:31,240 --> 00:08:34,240
 But what is this about them having personality?

231
00:08:34,240 --> 00:08:38,200
 So that is something which is called

232
00:08:38,200 --> 00:08:40,840
 ordinal linguistic personification.

233
00:08:40,840 --> 00:08:45,800
 So some letters and numbers have personalities

234
00:08:45,800 --> 00:08:46,960
 to people as soon as they see it.

235
00:08:46,960 --> 00:08:48,880
 So most of the numbers I find quite friendly,

236
00:08:48,880 --> 00:08:49,960
 apart from number five.

237
00:08:49,960 --> 00:08:51,360
 Sorry, quick question.

238
00:08:51,360 --> 00:08:53,440
 If there were a room of, say, 20 people

239
00:08:53,440 --> 00:08:55,880
 who all had this particular type of synesthesia,

240
00:08:55,880 --> 00:08:57,720
 would you all agree the colors?

241
00:08:57,720 --> 00:09:00,280
 You've all got your own separate colors.

242
00:09:00,280 --> 00:09:03,480
 I think there are some trends, if you like,

243
00:09:03,480 --> 00:09:05,600
 to some colors are picked more often.

244
00:09:05,600 --> 00:09:06,800
 They don't really know why.

245
00:09:06,800 --> 00:09:09,120
 Yeah, for example, the days of the week

246
00:09:09,120 --> 00:09:10,840
 have very fixed colors for me.

247
00:09:10,840 --> 00:09:13,080
 Most people, if you ask them what colors Monday,

248
00:09:13,080 --> 00:09:15,480
 we'll say blue, yeah, because of the blue Monday

249
00:09:15,480 --> 00:09:16,800
 or the association.

250
00:09:16,800 --> 00:09:20,000
 So you can predict quite often what people will say.

251
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:21,800
 But in synestheets, they're random.

252
00:09:21,800 --> 00:09:23,560
 There's another, which I find amazing.

253
00:09:23,560 --> 00:09:24,920
 I didn't know about all these varieties.

254
00:09:24,920 --> 00:09:27,760
 Oh, there's over 150 types of synesthesia

255
00:09:27,760 --> 00:09:29,000
 that they know of now.

256
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:31,760
 So the one I love most is mirror touch synesthesia.

257
00:09:31,760 --> 00:09:36,120
 That's what it is, where you feel what someone else feels.

258
00:09:36,120 --> 00:09:37,640
